Gilead Sciences Beats Q4 Views But Outlook Disappoints, Shares Fall
Gilead Sciences conference call ends.
Company has never been in better shape and will continue to look forward and invest in share buybacks, dividends and continued product strength.
Gilead has a large, sustainable market in Europe that will continue with healthy growth in the coming years.

The timing of our dividend reflects our confidence in our cash flow and balance sheet. Does not in any way prevent the company from investing in its business pipeline or M&A. We do not feel constrained in any way by issuing this dividend.
Gilead sales team has been a lot of time securing access in 2014 and will shift to drive demand in 2015.

Harvoni has proven to be effective on a much wider range of patients than previously thought, we are not concerned about future competition and this represents a very strong category for Gilead based on this profile.
70% of patients in 2014 came from the private sector
We are confident that we will see a large increase in patients across the US based on our goals to achieve greater accessibility.
Intentions for dividend are to grow over time, but at the moment they will still use share repurchases as the larger portion of the share returns in the near future.
Gilead conference call Q&A begins
CFO Washington: Expecting 2015 product sales to be $26-27B, increase of 6-10% over 2014
CFO Washington: Repaid $1B in outstanding debt in Q4
CFO Washington: HCV product sales $12.4B for 2014, helped by continued launches of Sovaldi and Harvoni and geographic expansion
Gilead Estimates 2015 Gross to Net Hepatitis C Drug Adjustments at 46% vs 22% at End  of 2014
CFO Washington: Cash flow will keep company strong and well positioned for any forthcoming M&A opportunities
CFO Washington: Annual yield of 1.6%, based on Monday's closing stock price
EVP Carter: HIV: In 2014, Gilead continues clinical and commercial success, $1.9B in sales in the Q4 and $6.3B in sales for the whole year, lead by Complera and Stribild
EVP Carter: 80% of new HIV patients started treament on a Gilead product, 70% of which were on Truvada
EVP Carter: We aim to streamline the process of access to treatment and therapy to at least 250,000 patients across all genotypes
EVP Carter: We expect 2015 gross to net adjustments in product in the US to be 46%, over double in 2014 which was 22%
EVP Carter: Sovaldi contributed $1.5B to European sales in 2014
EVP Carter: 140,000 have started HCV therapy on a Gilead product in the United States.

CEO Martin: Board has approved quarterly cash dividend program and $15B, 5-year repurchase. 2015 will be as busy as 2014, and will continue to provide collaboration and medication to those in need. I am proud of our progress thus far.
CEO Martin: GS-57945 Phase 2 studies are planned in Crohn's disease
CEO Martin: Progress continues in oncology and inflammation. Additional hires have been made to oncology, respiratory and inflammatory studies and departments.
CEO John Martin: Sovaldi has been approved in India and currently has 15,000 under treatment
